# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] General elections to the special Cortes of Cádiz were held in Spain in 1810.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 276 seats in the Cortes of Cádiz – which served as a parliamentary Regency after Ferdinand VII was deposed by Napoleon.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] During the first years of the Spanish War of Independence (1808-1814) the popular revolts of the Spanish people were accompanied by the creation of provincial and local defense "Juntas".
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] Those juntas assumed national sovereignty, forming their own local and regional governing bodies.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] These juntas aimed to defend against the French invasion and fill the power vacuum, refusing to recognize José I Bonaparte as their legitimate king.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] The juntas were mainly composed of military personnel, representatives of the high clergy, officials and professors.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] In September 1808 the local and provincial juntas ceded their power to the Supreme Central Government Junta of the Kingdom, which led the war against the French and was recognized as the legitimate government of Spain by the United Kingdom and other anti-Napoleonic countries.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] The Supreme Junta summoned an extraordinary meeting of the Cortes of Cádiz, a revolutionary act, since the right to call for a meeting of the Cortes was exclusive to the crown.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] After an intense debate in the Supreme Junta it was decided that the Cortes of Cádiz would be unicameral, elected by census suffrage (only those with a certain level of income could vote) and indirect.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] The Cortes met for the first time in the last major Spanish foothold during the Peninsular War, Cádiz, on the Isla de León, on September 24, 1810.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 32 multi-member constituencies and 2 single-member constituencies.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1810-spanish-general-election] All male citizens above 25 years old could vote or be voted.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1813-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1813.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1813-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 149 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1813-spanish-general-election] The 1813 elections were the first ones held since the approval of the 1812 Cádiz Constitution.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1813-spanish-general-election] All males over 21 years old, a total of 3,216,460 people, had the right to vote.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1820-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1820.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1820-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 203 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1820-spanish-general-election] The 1820 elections were the first ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1820-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Constitution of 1812.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1820-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 33 multi-member constituencies and various single-member ones.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1820-spanish-general-election] Most MPs were liberals, mainly from the *moderate* (or *doceañista*) faction.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1822-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1822.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1822-spanish-general-election] The 1822 elections were the second ones since the 1820 revolution.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1822-spanish-general-election] 3,215,460 people were eligible to vote (universal male suffrage), out of a population of 11,661,865.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1822-spanish-general-election] Almost all MPs were liberals, mainly from the radical *veinteañista* or *exaltada* faction.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1834-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in 1834.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1834-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 188 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1834-spanish-general-election] The 1834 elections were the first ones since 1822 and signalled the return of liberalism to Spain after the absolutist Década Ominosa.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1834-spanish-general-election] The elections were held under the Spanish Royal Statute of 1834, not under a full constitutional system.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1834-spanish-general-election] A first-past-the-post system was used with 48 multi-member constituencies and one single-member constituency.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1834-spanish-general-election] Only around 18,000 people were allowed to vote, out of a population of 12 million.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1837-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain in November 1837.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1837-spanish-general-election] At stake were all 241 seats in the Congress of Deputies.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1837-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 262,000 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1837-spanish-general-election] The elections were held on 22 September, at the peak of the First Carlist War.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1837-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 51 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1839-spanish-general-election] General elections to the Cortes Generales were held in Spain on 24 July 1839.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1839-spanish-general-election] Restricted census suffrage, only 376,255 people out of a total population of 12,162,872 were allowed to vote.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1839-spanish-general-election] A majority voting system was used for the election, with 48 multi-member constituencies and 1 single-member constituency.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] An election was held in Spain on 12 June 1994 as part of the concurrent EU-wide election to the 4th European Parliament.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] All 64 seats allocated to the Spanish constituency as per the 1993 Council Decision amending the Direct Elections Act were up for election.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] It was held concurrently with a regional election in Andalusia.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] The election was held against the backdrop of the early 1990s recession and a string of corruption scandals affecting the ruling Spanish Socialist Workers' Party (PSOE) of Prime Minister Felipe González.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] The People's Party (PP) won in a landslide victory, the first PP win over the PSOE in a nationwide election.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] 64 European Parliament seats were allocated to Spain as per the 1993 Council Decision amending the Direct Elections Act.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] All were elected in a single multi-member constituency—comprising the entire national territory—using the D'Hondt method and closed-list proportional voting, with no electoral threshold.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] The use of this electoral method resulted in an effective threshold depending on district magnitude and vote distribution.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] The law did not provide for by-elections to fill vacant seats; instead, any vacancies arising after the proclamation of candidates and during the legislative term were filled by the next candidates on the party lists or, when required, by designated substitutes.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] The table below shows the composition of the Spanish delegation in the chamber at the time of the election call.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] The electoral law allowed for parties and federations registered in the interior ministry, alliances and groupings of electors to present lists of candidates.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] Parties and federations intending to form an alliance were required to inform the relevant electoral commission within 10 days of the election call.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] Electors and elected officials were disallowed from signing for more than one list.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] The table below lists voting intention estimates in reverse chronological order, showing the most recent first and using the dates when the survey fieldwork was done, as opposed to the date of publication.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] Where the fieldwork dates are unknown, the date of publication is given instead.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] The highest percentage figure in each polling survey is displayed with its background shaded in the leading party's colour.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] If a tie ensues, this is applied to the figures with the highest percentages.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] The "Lead" column on the right shows the percentage-point difference between the parties with the highest percentages in a given poll.
[src:1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain/1994-european-parliament-election-in-spain] When available, seat projections are also displayed below the voting estimates in a smaller font.
